<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-8-1-general-concepts">
  <title>Vector-Valued Functions</title>

    <p>
      We now begin our study of the calculus of <term>multivariable functions</term>, i.e. functions of more than one scalar variable. You've likely studied the calculus of functions of a single variable, but many real-world applications of calculus involve the study of functions depending on multiple varying quantities.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-8-1-vector-valued-function">
      <p>
        A <term>vector-valued function</term> from <m>\R^n</m> to <m>\R^m</m>, is a function from <m>\R^n</m> to <m>\R^m</m>, typically denoted <m>\mathbf{f}: \R^n \to \R^m</m>. A <term>scalar-valued function</term> is a function <m>f: \R^n \to \R</m>, i.e. a vector-valued function from <m>\R^n</m> to <m>\R^m</m> with <m>m = 1</m>. Any vector-valued function <m>\mathbf{f}: \R^n \to \R^m</m> can be expressed in terms of <m>m</m> <term>component functions</term>, or <term>coordinate functions</term>, the scalar-valued functions <m>f_1, \dots, f_m: \R^n \to \R</m> such that
        <me>
          \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}) = ( f_1(\mathbf{x}), \dots, f_m(\mathbf{x}) )
        </me>.
        More generally, vector-valued and scalar-valued functions may only be defined on a subset of vectors in <m>\R^n</m>, rather than defined everywhere, i.e. their <term>domain</term> may be a proper subset of <m>\R^n</m>.
      </p>
    </definition>

    <p>
      In other words, a scalar-valued function takes in an input and outputs <em>scalars</em>, and a vector-valued function takes in an input and outputs <em>vectors</em> (recall <xref ref="def-1-0-scalars-and-vectors"/>). 
    </p>

    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\mathbf{x}</m> is a point in <m>\R^n</m>, recall the length of <m>\mathbf{x}</m>, denoted <m>\| \mathbf{x} \|</m>, from <xref ref="def-1-1-vector-length"/>. The length of a vector defines a scalar-valued function from <m>\R^n</m> to <m>\R</m>, i.e. the function which takes in a vector <m>\mathbf{x}</m> as input and gives the length <m>\| \mathbf{x} \|</m> as output. Show that this function has the property that two different inputs can have the same output. Recall from <xref ref="def-5-4-inject-and-surject"/> that we say this function is <em>not injective</em>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          There are many different choices one could make here. For instance, the vector <m>(3,4)</m> and the vector <m>(5,0)</m> both have the same length. Other examples are the vectors <m>(1,2)</m> and <m>(-1,2)</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <activity>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix. The linear transformation (recall <xref ref="def-2-4-linear-transformation"/>) <m>T: \R^n \to \R^m</m> defined by <m>T(\mathbf{x}) = T_A(\mathbf{x}) = A\mathbf{x}</m> is a vector-valued function.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
           If <m>\mathbf{a}_1, \dots, \mathbf{a}_m</m> are the rows of <m>A</m>, and <m>T_1, \dots, T_m</m> are the component functions of <m>T</m>, then for each <m>j</m>, express the function <m>T_j</m> in terms of the row <m>\mathbf{a}_j</m>.
         </p>
       </statement>

       <solution>
        <p>
          Recalling the definition of matrix vector multiplication from <xref ref="def-2-2-matrix-vector-product"/>, we can write
          <me>
            T_j(\mathbf{x}) = \mathbf{a}_{j1} x_1 + \cdots + \mathbf{a}_{jn} x_n = \mathbf{a}_j \cdot \mathbf{x}
          </me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the matrix
          <me>A = \begin{pmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 3 &amp; 4 \end{pmatrix}</me>,
          which defines a linear transformation <m>T_A: \R^3 \to \R^2</m>. Compute its component functions for a general input <m>\mathbf{x}</m>, and its output for the specific input <m>\mathbf{x} = (3, -1, 2)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The component functions are:

          <me>T_1(\mathbf{x}) = (1,2,-1) \cdot \mathbf{x} = x_1 + 2 x_2 - x_3</me>

          and

          <me>T_2(\mathbf{x}) = (0,3,4) \cdot \mathbf{x} = 3x_2 + 4x_3</me>.

          For an input <m>\mathbf{x} = (3, -1, 2)</m>, we compute that

          <me>T(\mathbf{x}) = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp 4 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </activity>
</section>